<h2>The Last Passenger</h2>
<p>
    Every night at exactly 11:47 PM, the old city bus stopped at the abandoned terminal even though no routes were scheduled there anymore. Drivers who worked the late shift claimed they sometimes saw a pale woman standing beneath the flickering streetlight, holding a torn red umbrella. She never moved or waved, but if the driver opened the doors, she would quietly climb aboard and sit in the very last seat. The strange part was that no security camera ever captured her entering the bus. Yet every morning, muddy footprints appeared in the aisle leading to the back.
</p>
<br>
<p>
    One driver named Arturo decided to confront her after hearing the rumors for months. As he drove through the empty streets, he watched her reflection carefully through the overhead mirror. Her face looked blurred, almost smeared, as though water had soaked through a photograph. When he finally gathered enough courage to ask where she was headed, she answered in a cracked whisper, “You already passed it.” At that moment, every passenger on the bus slowly turned to stare at him, even though he had been alone the entire route.
</p>
<br>
<p>
    The bus suddenly died in the middle of a bridge, and all the lights went out except the dim emergency lamp above the rear seat. Arturo looked back and saw the woman standing in the aisle, inches away from him despite the distance. Her mouth stretched wider than humanly possible as she pointed toward the river below. The next morning, the empty bus was discovered abandoned on the bridge with the doors wide open and the engine still running. Arturo was never found, but commuters still report seeing a lone figure sitting in the last seat whenever the bus passes the river at night.
</p>